art defect in which the two main arteries leaving the heart are switched. This condition can lead to significant problems with blood circulation and oxygen delivery throughout the body.", "Symptoms": "Symptoms of this condition include cyanosis (bluish discoloration of the skin and lips due to low oxygen), shortness of breath, lack of appetite, and poor weight gain. These symptoms can manifest in infants and children.", "Treatments": {"Medications": {"Prostaglandins": {"Use": "Prostaglandins are medications that help improve blood flow in infants with transposition of the great arteries. They work by keeping the ductus arteriosus (a blood vessel that normally closes) open, allowing blood to circulate more effectively.", "Side Effects": "Side effects of prostaglandins may include fever, diarrhea, and changes in heart rate. These medications can also cause gastrointestinal symptoms that may be noticeable in some infants."}}, "Surgery": {"Arterial Switch Operation": {"Use": "The arterial switch operation is a complex surgical procedure in which the great arteries are repositioned to their correct locations, thereby restoring normal heart function.", "Side Effects": "Possible side effects among patients include infections, bleeding, and the potential need for additional surgeries in the future. Patients may also experience emotional and physical changes, particularly during recovery."}}}}}